## Lessons Learned

- PDF files retain metadata from the original document — author, creation date, software used
- Images contain EXIF data including GPS coordinates that reveal exact location
- Always strip metadata before sharing sensitive documents or images
- Forensic tools like pdfinfo and exiftool can reveal hidden information instantly
- GPS coordinates in images can pinpoint exact crime scene locations
- Hidden data (steganography) can exist in User Comment fields

## Defender's Perspective / Privacy Tips

- Use metadata stripping tools before sharing documents publicly
- Disable GPS tagging on smartphone cameras for privacy
- Use PDF sanitizers to remove author information before publishing
- Be aware that MS Word embeds author name automatically
- ExifTool can be used to remove metadata: `exiftool -all= image.jpg`

## Attacker's Perspective

- Always strip metadata from files before sending — it reveals identity
- GPS coordinates in images can expose your physical location
- PDF metadata reveals what software and username created the document
- These mistakes have caught real criminals in real cases

